[1] India (West Bengal)
Date: Tue 23 Aug 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Xinhua, China, 23 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-08/23/content_3392870.htm>

Dengue kills 4 persons in India's Kolkata (Calcutta) city
-----------------------------------------------
Dengue has claimed 4 lives in one week in the Eastern Indian city of
Kolkata, not even sparing the city's upscale neighborhoods, local news
agency Indo-Asian News Agency (IANS) reported on Tuesday [23 Aug 2005].
Kolkata, one of the 4 major Indian metropolitan cities, is also the capital
of the eastern Indian state of West Bengal.
According to IANS reports, West Bengal Health Chief Prabhakar Chatterjee
has admitted that the fever that swept through some areas of south Kolkata
is dengue or brain fever.
"We have got reports of 4 deaths so far, 2 each in 2 private hospitals of
Kolkata. Blood tests have revealed the presence of dengue in 8 other
people," Chatterjee told IANS Tuesday [23 Aug 2005]. The unofficial death
toll is said to be 7.
"We have instructed all medical colleges and hospitals to contact the
School of Tropical Medicine and National Institute of Cholera and Enteric
Diseases (NICED) whenever they find a patient with dengue symptoms,"
Chatterjee said.
Health officials said about 100 people suffering from fever were showing
symptoms of dengue, which often causes death when the fever reaches the
brain. The disease spreads through the bite of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
Reservoirs constructed for scores of big and small housing projects, water
collected in road excavation sites, accumulated garbage and rooftop water
accumulation are the breeding ground of the _Aedes_ mosquito.
An emergency meeting was held Monday [22 Aug 2005] between the Kolkata
Municipal Corporation (KMC) and the state health department to combat
dengue, the reports said.
