[3] India (Calcutta)
Date: Sat 20 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Cities.epressindia.com, 20 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=144826>

KMC confirms city's 1st dengue death
-------------------------------------------
2 other persons have reportedly died after suffering from the viral fever
that has hit wards 92, 94, and 97, Express News Service reported.
The city's 1st case of dengue fever has been "officially" confirmed by the
health department of the Kolkata Municipal Corporation [KMC].
Several cases of people falling sick with viral fever have also been
reported from various wards in southern parts of the city.
Dr. Dipankar Das, deputy chief municipal health officer, told Newsline that
a resident from ward 40 under KMC has been found to be suffering from
dengue. "The patient is under treatment at a private city hospital. This is
the 1st and only case of dengue that has come to our notice under the KMC
area," said Das.
In another incident, 2 other persons have reportedly died after suffering
from the viral fever that is on the rise and has affected people living in
wards 92, 94, 97 and the adjoining localities of other wards.
Ratan Dey, councilor of ward 93, told Newsline that 2 residents of
Masjidpara, in ward 93, have died due to viral fever.
"3 deaths have also taken place in ward 94. Over a 100 people are suffering
from viral fever in my ward alone. This figure is on basis of people's
complaints. To provide some immediate relief, the KMC has put up a health
camp at Masjidpara. Since morning today [20 Aug 2005], 86 people have
visited the camp for a check up," said Dey.
2 KMC doctors are on duty at the said health camp for the 1st half of the
day. Dey, however, said that the incidence of fever is high, and the
available aid is inadequate. "The problem is much bigger for the KMC to
tackle. On behalf of the local councilors, I request the state to provide
help at a larger scale," said Dey.
Member of the mayor-in-council (health) Dr. Subhod Kumar Dey said that the
reported deaths under the KMC are probably due to viral fever.
"We are probing into the cause. It is difficult to say whether the deaths
in Masjidpara and the adjoining locality, as reported by the local
councilor, are due to dengue," said Dey.
"Information available with me suggests that, under the KMC, only one
person has been found to be suffering from dengue. One case has been
reported in Salt Lake and 2 in Dum Dum. On our part, we are taking the
necessary steps," Dey added.
--
