[4] Cambodia
Date: Tue 23 Aug 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: People's Daily Online, China, 23 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200508/23/eng20050823_204169.html>

Cambodia has fewer dengue cases in children this year [2005], thanks to the
ongoing dengue prevention efforts by the government, local media reported
on Tuesday [23 Aug 2005].
Statistics from the Ministry of Health show that, so far this year [2005],
an estimated 4300 children across the country have contracted dengue fever,
and 68 of them have died of dengue hemorrhagic fever, the lethal form of
this mosquito-borne disease.
The death rate among children sickened by dengue is roughly half of the
fatality rate during the same period last year [2004], according to health
officials.
"If we compare the situation with last year [2004], we are doing better
this year," The Cambodia Daily quoted Mam Bunheng, secretary of state for
the Health Ministry, as saying. "The management of the program is going well."
In Siem Reap province, where a significant outbreak of dengue fever
occurred 2 years ago, this year [2005] only 5 or 6 dengue cases a month
were treated in Angkor Hospital for Children, where a good portion of
patients from surrounding provinces come for treatment.
"We have not seen an increase in the past couple of years like we did in
2003," Ngoun Chan Theaktra, medical director of the hospital, said.
Mam Bunheng said that the lower figures are a testament to ongoing dengue
prevention campaigns, including using insecticides to kill mosquitoes and
larvae, and educating parents to protect their youngsters from the
disease-carrying insects.
But health officials say the disease remains a significant concern. They
hope that, by the end of the year [2005], the number of dengue cases will
continue to drop.
