[6] Indonesia (Jakarta)
Date: Tue 23 Aug 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Today Online, Indonesia, 22 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/68098.asp>

Dengue deaths reach 605 in Indonesia this year [2005]
-----------------------------------------------
Indonesia has recorded 605 dengue fever deaths this year [2005] but has
avoided any "extraordinary outbreak," a health official told AFP.
The health ministry's Rita Kusriastuti said that 43 509 infections had been
reported, boosting the incidence rate to 19.6 per 100 000 residents from
18.8 for the same period last year [2004]. But she said no "extraordinary"
outbreaks had occurred, as officials stepped up public information
campaigns to combat the mosquito-borne disease.
"It is true that the figure is high, but there are yet no areas where the
spread of the dengue can be declared as having reached an extraordinary
stage," Kusriastuti told AFP. Extraordinary outbreaks, defined as when the
death rate exceeds 2 percent of those infected, were declared in 12 of
Indonesia's 32 provinces last year [2004].
The official said health authorities were still paying particular attention
to outbreaks in North Sumatra, West Sumatra and Jakarta.
Dengue is an annual hazard for Indonesians. Last year [2004] it killed 800
people and infected 79 480 others.
