[7] Philippines
Date: Mon 22 Aug 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Philippine Information Agency, Philippines, 22 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.pia.gov.ph/news.asp?fi=p050822.htm&no=7>

Health officer reiterates campaign against dengue
-----------------------------------------------
Dengue cases continue to rise, with 78 cases reported since January of this
year [2005].
Dr. Nelly Abiera, Provincial Health Officer, said death cases had been
reported from the towns of San Remigio, Tobias Fornier and Culasi, each
town having had one death each.
"In the current situation, people should continue to intensify the
cleanliness campaign and the preventive measures undertaken to ensure that
the breeding places of _Aedes aegypti_, the dengue carrier mosquito, are
eliminated.
Flower vases, flower petals, bromeliads and old tires should be removed and
cleaned, as this type of mosquito thrives in clean standing water."
Abiera campaigned for "tepok kiti-kiti" ("goodbye dengue").
Dr. Abiera also stressed that the utmost care and close observation must be
taken, especially when symptoms of dengue, like fever, rashes and bleeding
or hemorrhage, appear. Medical help should be sought right away. She also
forewarned about the use of "aspirin or aspilet," which must never be
administered to children sick of dengue, for they will only aggravate the
situation.
"The massive information campaign must be coupled with the distribution of
the brochure 'How to Manage Dengue,'" Dr. Abiera concluded.
[Byline: EA Abasquez]
